Here's what happened and how to fix it:

## What changed

In **.NET 11**, `DSA.Create()` now throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on **macOS** (PR [dotnet/runtime#119182](https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/pull/119182), milestone 11.0.0). macOS joins iOS/tvOS/Mac Catalyst, where DSA was already unsupported since .NET 6.

**Why:** Apple's Security framework has limited/deprecated DSA support, and NIST deprecated DSA for digital signatures in FIPS 186-5. The .NET team removed the `DSASecurityTransforms` backend that previously bridged DSA on macOS via Apple's framework.

## How to fix it

**Option 1 — Use `DSAOpenSsl` on macOS** (minimal change, requires OpenSSL):

```csharp
using System.Security.Cryptography;

DSA dsa;
if (DSA.IsSupported)
{
    dsa = DSA.Create();           // Windows, Linux
}
else if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
{
    dsa = new DSAOpenSsl();       // macOS via OpenSSL
}
else
{
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA is not supported on this platform.");
}
```

This requires OpenSSL on macOS (e.g., `brew install openssl`).

**Option 2 — Use BouncyCastle** (no native dependency):

```xml
<PackageReference Include="BouncyCastle.Cryptography" Version="2.*" />
```
```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
verifier.Init(false, publicKeyParameters);
verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
```

**Option 3 — Migrate away from DSA** (best long-term):  
Since DSA is deprecated by NIST, consider re-signing with **ECDSA** or **RSA** if you control the signing infrastructure. This is the most future-proof path.

### Detection tip

Use `DSA.IsSupported` (added in .NET 6) to guard DSA code paths at runtime so you can fail gracefully instead of catching exceptions.
